XVIII · BAYOU NIGHT
The Moon
Visual / Historical Framing
The bayou at night is a landscape of illusion and ambiguity. What you see in the moonlight is already partly a ghost of itself, as Louisiana loses an approximate football field of coastal wetland every hour. The feu follet (will-o'-the-wisp) is explained both as methane igniting above decomposing matter, and in folklore, as the soul of an unbaptized child or an enslaved person who died without proper rites. The natural phenomenon and the supernatural interpretation coexist without resolution.
