XXI · MARDI GRAS INDIANS
The World
Visual / Historical Framing
The Mardi Gras Indian in full regalia represents the culmination of a year of private labor made public through a confrontation ritual judged only by artistry. The tradition honors the Indigenous tribes—particularly the Choctaw and Houma—who sheltered and intermarried with Black communities. The specific greeting between rival tribes—"Handa wanda" and "Tchopitoulas"—precedes the confrontation, which transformed over decades into a competition of art. "Pretty" is the highest praise in the tradition. The World card is the moment of full emergence before the work begins again; the completion immediately seeds the next cycle.
